#################################################################
# Source 3 — Commentary by Kingsley Uyi Idehen
#################################################################

:commentary a schema:Comment ;
    schema:name "Agent context, identity, and preferences — commentary"@en ;
    schema:author :kingsleyIdehen ;
    schema:dateCreated "2026-07-18"^^xsd:date ;
    schema:about :termProfile, :termLangulator, :termUnix, :thesis ;
    schema:text "Agent context naturally informs agent behavior, but marketing communications around the topic overlook the power RDF brings to it. Unix and its derivatives handle identity and preferences as fundamental components of the operating-system bridge between users and computer services — a foundational principle blurred over the years by command-line and graphical interfaces. Large language models ('langulators') now offer a new multimodal, multilingual interface for driving computers, yet the fundamentals of identity and preferences — session context via profiles — have been lost in AI's repositioning of the software industry. One of AI's most powerful benefits is recapturing identity and preferences as the foundation for context: an operating framework for LLMs, AI agents, skills, and everything loosely coupled with data spaces including databases, knowledge bases, filesystems, and APIs. The era of meaningless buzzwords pushed via mantra-like chants is dead, because conversing with your tools eliminates every reason to be distracted by superficial labels that land you in the next technical-debt-compounding silo."@en .

