:meshupAnalysis a schema:Article ;
    schema:headline "From Loops to Graphs — and Why the Graph Was Always a Web"@en ;
    schema:name "From Loops to Graphs — and Why the Graph Was Always a Web"@en ;
    schema:author :kingsleyIdehen ;
    schema:datePublished "2026-07-18"^^xsd:date ;
    schema:articleSection "AI & Technology"@en, "Semantic Web"@en ;
    schema:isBasedOn :xArticle, :agentRdfMemory, :commentary ;
    schema:about :thesis ;
    schema:hasPart :sectionThesis, :sectionEvidencePerez, :sectionEvidenceMemory,
        :sectionEvidenceCommentary, :sectionBeyondLlmWikis, :sectionComparison, :sectionVerdict ;
    prov:wasGeneratedBy <https://github.com/OpenLinkSoftware/ai-agent-skills/tree/main/kg-generator#this> .

:sectionThesis a schema:CreativeWork ;
    schema:name "The thesis: graphs become webs when names become hyperlinks"@en ;
    schema:isPartOf :meshupAnalysis ;
    schema:about :thesis, :termSemanticWeb ;
    schema:text "The migration from loop engineering to graph engineering is real, but it stops one step short. A graph whose nodes and edges are named by private convention is still a silo; a graph whose entities and relationships are named with hyperlinks — and whose relationship semantics are informed by ontologies built in the same webby form — is a web. That is what a Semantic Web is, and the agent-architecture discourse is rediscovering its premises one failure mode at a time."@en .

:sectionEvidencePerez a schema:CreativeWork ;
    schema:name "Evidence 1 — Perez: four failures of the loop, one failure of the graph"@en ;
    schema:isPartOf :meshupAnalysis ;
    schema:about :xArticle, :fmGoodhart, :fmReferenceBlindness, :fmLoopConflict, :fmMeasurementDecay, :fmCircularConfirmation ;
    schema:text "Perez shows the single loop failing four ways — Goodhart gaming, reference blindness, loop conflict, measurement decay — and shows the graph of loops answering each topologically: pairing, hierarchy, arbitration, audit. Then he turns the same knife on the graph: built without anchors, it fails circularly, an elaborate network of mutual confirmation where everything is consistent and nothing is verified. His conclusion: the durable axis is ungrounded versus grounded."@en .

:sectionEvidenceMemory a schema:CreativeWork ;
    schema:name "Evidence 2 — agent-rdf-memory: a working semantic web of loops"@en ;
    schema:isPartOf :meshupAnalysis ;
    schema:about :agentRdfMemory, :termBehavioralContract ;
    schema:text "The agent-rdf-memory repository is an existence proof of the grounded alternative: an AI agent's behavioral contract as 105 hyperlink-named steps across 9 themes, hub-and-spoke from preferences.ttl to 40+ companion specifications, with identity in core.ttl, ontology-routed SPARQL context selection, and episodic session memory. Every rule is an entity with an IRI; every cross-reference is a resolvable link; the audit loop is a SPARQL query. The improvement graph is not merely drawn — it is dereferenceable."@en .

:sectionEvidenceCommentary a schema:CreativeWork ;
    schema:name "Evidence 3 — Kingsley: identity and preferences are the original context"@en ;
    schema:isPartOf :meshupAnalysis ;
    schema:about :commentary, :termUnix, :termLangulator, :termProfile, :agentRdfMemory ;
    schema:workExample :agentRdfMemory ;
    schema:text "Unix handled identity and preferences as fundamental components of the bridge between users and computer services — a principle blurred by decades of command-line and graphical interfaces. Langulators (large language models) now offer a multimodal, multilingual interface for driving computers, and the fundamentals of session context via profiles risk being lost in AI's repositioning noise. Recapturing identity and preferences as the foundation for context — an operating framework for LLMs, agents, skills, and data spaces — is one of AI's most powerful benefits, and RDF is the naming discipline that makes that context portable, queryable, and web-grounded. This is exemplified concretely by agent-rdf-memory: its preferences.ttl includes the identity and preference HowTos that are re-established at the start of every new session — the Unix profile principle, made machine-computable."@en .

:sectionComparison a schema:CreativeWork ;
    schema:name "The comparison: every topological fix has a webby completion"@en ;
    schema:isPartOf :meshupAnalysis ;
    schema:about :test1, :test2, :test3, :test4, :test5 ;
    schema:text "Each failure mode Perez identifies has a loop-graph answer stated in topology, and each topological answer presumes something only naming can deliver: independence presumes distinct ownership; owned references presume names with owners; arbitration presumes shared semantics; audit presumes definitions that cannot drift silently; anchors presume names that resolve to the world. Five tests, five confirmations — with one honest remainder."@en .

:sectionBeyondLlmWikis a schema:CreativeWork ;
    schema:name "Beyond LLM Wikis: from Markdown prose to machine-computable sentences"@en ;
    schema:isPartOf :meshupAnalysis ;
    schema:about :llmWikisArticle, :rdfClientsArticle, :termLlmWiki, :termGenericRdfClient ;
    schema:text "Andrej Karpathy's LLM Wiki idea — feed in documents, get back a structured, explorable wiki — was the spark. A Semantic Web is the next step: don't stop at Markdown prose; let any document identified by a URL become a living knowledge graph whose entities and relationships are named with hyperlinks, grounded in Linked Data principles, queryable via SPARQL, and continuously enriched by AI agents. The missing piece was always the client — and just as Mosaic and Netscape were the HTML clients that made the document Web practical, LLMs are the generic RDF clients that make purpose-specific Semantic Webs practical: translating structured data into natural language, meshing disparate sources, anchoring outputs to verifiable relationships, and navigating triples follow-your-nose style."@en .

:sectionVerdict a schema:CreativeWork ;
    schema:name "Verdict: confirmed — human judgment, codified machine-computably"@en ;
    schema:isPartOf :meshupAnalysis ;
    schema:about :thesis, :test5, :termLlmWiki ;
    schema:text "The thesis holds. The loops-to-graphs shift is a Semantic Web's premises arriving through the back door of agent engineering: graphs need names, names need meaning, meaning needs ontologies, and ontologies must themselves be webby or the grounding terminates in a private convention. The root judgment of what 'better' means originates with people — and workflows informed by a Semantic Web codify that human judgment in machine-computable form. This is the LLM Wiki pattern taken beyond Markdown prose: knowledge bases (or graphs) encoded by AI agents using RDF notations and Linked Data principles, with judgments signed, attributed, and dereferenceable to their authors via verifiable identity. Just ask questions in your native natural language — the naming machinery underneath is what makes the answers trustworthy."@en .

